name.text: 12.2.2.1 Distinguishing between local maxima and minima

questiontext.text:
Distinguishing between local maxima and minima


We might ask if it is possible to predict when a stationary point is a local maximum, a local minimum or a point of inflection without the necessity of drawing the curve. To do this we highlight the general characteristics of curves in the neighbourhood of local maxima and minima.

For example: at a local maximum (located at \(x_0\) say) describes the situation:

To the left of the maximum \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}f}{\mathrm{d}x}>0\)

To the right of the maximum \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}f}{\mathrm{d}x}<0\)


If we draw a graph of the derivative \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}f}{\mathrm{d}x}\) against \(x\) then, near a local maximum, it must take one of two basic shapes described:

In case (a) \( \dfrac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}x}\left(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}f}{\mathrm{d}x}\right)\bigg|_{x_0}\equiv \tan\alpha<0\) whilst in case (b) \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}x}\left(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}f}{\mathrm{d}x}\right)\bigg|_{x_0}=0\).

We reach the conclusion that at a stationary point which is a maximum the value of the second derivative \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}^2f}{\mathrm{d} x^2}\) is either negative or zero.

Near a local minimum the above graphs are inverted. Below shows a local minimum.

To the left of the minimum \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}f}{\mathrm{d}x}<0\)

To the right of the minimum \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}f}{\mathrm{d}x}>0\)

The figure below shows the two possible graphs of the derivative:

Here, for case (a) \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}x}\left(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}f}{\mathrm{d}x}\right)\bigg|_{x_0}=\tan\beta >0\) whilst in (b) \( \dfrac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}x}\left(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}f}{\mathrm{d}x}\right)\bigg|_{x_0}=0.\).

In this case we conclude that at a stationary point which is a minimum the value of the second derivative \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d} ^2f}{\mathrm{d} x^2}\) is either positive or zero. For the third possibility for a stationary point - a point of inflection - the graph of \(f(x)\) against \(x\) and of \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}f}{\mathrm{d}x}\) against \(x\) take one of two forms as shown below.

For either of these cases \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}x}\left(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}f}{\mathrm{d}x}\right)\bigg|_{x_0}=0\)

The sketches and analysis of the shape of a curve \(y=f(x)\) in the near neighbourhood of stationary points allow us to make the following important deduction:

A generalisation of the third law of indices states:

Key Point

If \(x_0\) locates a stationary point of \(f(x)\), so that \(\displaystyle \frac{\mathrm{d}f}{\mathrm{d}x}\|_{x_0}= 0\), then the stationary point

\(\quad\) is a local minimum if \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}^2f}{\mathrm{d}x^2}\bigg|_{x_0}>0\)

\(\quad\) is a local maximum if \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}^2f}{\mathrm{d}x^2}\bigg|_{x_0}<0\)

\(\quad\) is inconclusive if \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}^2f}{\mathrm{d}x^2}\bigg|_{x_0}=0\).

Example

Find the stationary points of the function \(f(x)=x^3-6x\).

Are these stationary points local maxima or local minima?

Solution

\(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}f}{\mathrm{d}x}= 3x^2−6\). At a stationary point \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}f}{\mathrm{d}x}= 0\) so \(3x^2−6 = 0\), implying \(x=\pm\sqrt{2}\).Thus \(f(x)\) has stationary points at \(x=\sqrt{2}\)and\(x=−\sqrt{2}\). To decide if these are maxima or minima we examine the value of the second derivative of \(f(x)\)at the stationary points.

\(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}^2f}{\mathrm{d}x^2}= 6x\) so \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}^2f}{\mathrm{d}x^2}\bigg|_{x=\sqrt{2}}= 6\sqrt{2}>0\). Hence \(x=\sqrt{2}\) locates a local minimum.

Similarly \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}^2f}{\mathrm{d}x^2}\bigg|_{x=−\sqrt{2}}=−6\sqrt{2}<0\). Hence \(x=−\sqrt{2}\) locates a local maximum.
